edtime Story'' (\u7761\u524d\u6545\u4e8b)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n| ''Mission Landing'' \u300e\u767b\u9678\u8a08\u756b\u300f\n|[[Silence Wong]]\n|-\n|''To Home'' (\u5beb\u4fe1\u56de\u5bb6)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Wish You Well'' \u300e\u6211\u8981\u4f60\u597d\u597d\u7684\u300f\n|[[Rene Liu]]\n|-\n|''Wish You Well'' (\u6211\u8981\u4f60\u597d\u597d\u7684)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n|[[Rene Liu]] feat. [[Zhou Xun]]\u3001[[Gwei Lun-mei]]\u3001[[Tang Wei]]\n|lyrics revision\n|-\n|''Be My Own Friend'' (\u7576\u6211\u7684\u597d\u670b\u53cb)\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2016\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Be My Own Friend'' \u300e\u7576\u6211\u7684\u597d\u670b\u53cb\u300f\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Della\n|\n|-\n|''Get Your Move On '' (\u5927\u52d5\u4f5c)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n|lyrics revision\n|-\n|''Still Missing'' (\u9084\u662f\u60f3\u5ff5)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Y}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Still Missing'' \u300e\u9084\u662f\u60f3\u5ff5\u300f\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\u5bb6\u5bb6\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n|-\n|''Smooth Love'' (\u76f8\u611b\u7121\u4e8b)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Y}}\n|-\n|''Brighter Sky, Darker Night'' (\u5929\u8d8a\u4eae\uff0c\u591c\u8d8a\u9ed1)\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2017\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''No. 13 \u2013 A Dancing Van Gogh'' \u300e\u8df3\u821e\u7684\u68b5\u8c37\u300f\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Stefanie Sun\n|-\n|''Happy Normal'' (\u5e73\u65e5\u5feb\u6a02)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n|-\n|''Nothing is Missing'' (\u4e0d\u7f3a)\n|{{Y}}\n|{{Nay}}\n| ''Nine Ways to Enjoy Loneliness'' \u300e\u4e5d\u7a2e\u4f7f\u7528\u5b64\u7368\u7684\u6b63\u78ba\u65b9\u5f0f\u300f\n|[[Michael Wong (singer)|Michael]]\n|}\n\n=== Collaboration ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\"   \n!Year released\n!Singer\n!Song title\n!Album\n|-\n|2015\n|Easy Shen\n|''Afterdark'' (\u4e8b\u5f8c)\n|''Anatta'' \u300e\u5982\u679c\u8eab\u9ad4\u5168\u90e8\u958b\u653e\u4e86\u300f\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== Golden Melody ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background: rgb(255, 255, 255); margin-bottom: 109px;\" width=\"50%\"\n!Year \n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Album\n! Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | 2015\n| Best Lyricist\n| Lala Hsu\uff0f''Missing''\n|''Missing''\u300e\u5c0b\u4eba\u555f\u4e8b\u300f|| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n=== Association of Musicians in Taiwan ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\" \n! colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | Top ten singles\n|- style=\"height: 40px;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Song title\n! colspan=\"2\" |Contribution\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Singer\n! rowspan=\"2\" |note\n|-\n!Lyrics\n!Comp.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2014 \n| ''Missing'' (\u5c0b\u4eba\u555f\u4e8b) ||{{yes}}\n|<br> \n|[[Lala Hsu]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ent.ltn.com.tw/news/breakingnews/1340943|title=Hush\u5165\u570d\u6700\u4f73\u4f5c\u8a5e\u4eba \u611f\u8b1d\u71d5\u59ff\u958b\u555f\u5275\u4f5c\u8def|last=\u8521\u741b\u5100|date=June 6, 2015|work=Liberty Times|language=zh-hant|access-date=29 June 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''Kepler'' (\u514b\u535c\u52d2) ||{{yes}}|| {{yes}} \n|[[Stephanie Sun]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hush}}\n[[Category:LGBT singers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese lyricists]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese male singers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese Mandopop singers]]\n[[Category:People from Pingtung County]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese composers]]\n[[Category:Taiwanese singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mandopop singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Gay musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Taiwanese singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCredits:clean up, replaced:  \u3001 \u2192 , (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hush_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "Tyer's Electric Train Tablet", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Globalize|date=August 2008}}\n\n'''Tyer's Electric Train Tablet''' system is a form of [[railway signalling]] for [[Single track (rail)|single line]] railways used in several countries; it was first devised in Great Britain by engineer {{Interlanguage link multi|Edward Tyer|lb}} after the [[Thorpe rail accident]] of 1874, which left 21 people dead.{{sfn|Faith|2000|p=44}} It was used in New Zealand for close to 100 years until June 1994.\nThe system used a hard disk called a ''tablet'', a form of [[Token (railway signalling)|token]]. \n\nThe purpose of the system was to use the tablet as a physical guarantee to the traincrew that their train had exclusive right of way on the single line section. Without this they could not proceed beyond the section signal which protected entry to the single line. \n\nWith advances in electrical locking of the [[lever frame]] within the [[signal box]], the tablet instrument also electrically locked the section signal lever. This was marked with a white stripe on the red background.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-1.JPG|thumb|Main view of No. 6 instrument showing the restoring lever and the tablet tray in the \"out\" position]]\n\nAn instrument was placed at each end of the single-track section that they were to control. They were connected together electrically in such a way that operation of one would depend on operations carried out using the other.\n\nThere were various incarnations of instruments developed by Tyer & Co. Below are the more commonly found ones:\n\nThe Tyer's no. 7 tablet instrument consists of a wooden case, on top of which is a metal slide, a switch plunger, a bell plunger and an electric current indicator. On the front is an indicator which may show either of three indications: \"Line Closed\"; \"Train Approaching\" and \"Train on Line\". Below this there is a second slide, which has three positions: fully home, withdrawn half way, and fully withdrawn. The three indications correspond to the three positions of the slide. The case contains several tablets; they are removed from the instrument using the bottom slide, and replaced using the top slide. The instrument was so constructed that if a tablet had been withdrawn from either instrument of a pair, no further tablets could be withdrawn until the withdrawn tablet had been placed either in the other instrument, or in the same instrument from which it had been withdrawn.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=121}}\n\nThe Tyer's no. 6 tablet instrument is cast iron framed that has a movable drawer at the front which issues and receives the tablets. On the left hand side is a lever to reseat the tablet when it is replaced into the magazine. It has wooden side cheeks to access the complicated mechanism and a tombstone shaped wooden case on the top which houses the bell plunger, commutator and the tablet indicators for up and down trains. At the very top was the [[galvanometer]]. The [[British absolute block signalling|signalling bell]] associated with the machine is separate so could be located on the block shelf or wall mounted above the instrument.\n\n===Tablets===\nTablets are in the form of a disc made of metal or fibre (with a gunmetal weight at the top of the magazine), engraved with the names of the stations between which it is valid, and also provided with notches (also called configurations) or other indentations to ensure that it would fit only one pair of instruments. They were often painted in distinctive colours as an additional visual identification in areas where consecutive sections could each be controlled using the same type of instrument. The diameter of the tablets varied between the different patterns of instrument: those for the No 1 were the largest, the smallest were for the No 5 and No 7, whilst the Nos 2,3,4 and 6 all used tablets about {{convert|4.5|in|mm}} in diameter.\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-11.JPG|thumb|The indicators showing a tablet has been issued for an Up train from this instrument]]\nThe system required each station at the end of each section to be staffed, the staff member would communicate with the staff member at the other end of the section with a bell code to release a tablet.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=121}}\n\nTo release a tablet at station A to send a train to station B:\n* Both machines must be in a closed state\n* Operator at station A sends a bell code to station B asking if line is clear for the train\n* If clear, operator at station B will repeat the bell code to acknowledge\n* Station A operator holds down the bell plunger\n* Station B operator presses his/her switch plunger with one hand, and with the other pulls out the bottom slide half-way; the instrument now shows a \"Train Approaching\" indication\n* Station B operator holds down the bell plunger\n* Station A operator presses his/her switch plunger with one hand, and with the other pulls the bottom slide to its full extent; the instrument now shows a \"Train on Line\" indication and releases a tablet from the lower slide\n* Station A operator hands the tablet to the driver of the train heading to station B\n\nTo close up each machine once the train has arrived at station B from station A:\n* The train driver hands the tablet to station B operator\n* Station B operator draws out the top slide, places the tablet in it, and closes the top and then the bottom slide; the instrument now shows a \"Line Closed\" indication\n* Station B operator sends a bell code to station A (denoting \"Train out of Section\"), holding the plunger down on the last stroke\n* Station A operator holds down his switch plunger, and closes the bottom slide; the instrument now shows a \"Line Closed\" indication\n* Both machines are now in closed states ready for the process to start again for another train\n\nThe original Tyer's No. 1 instrument was a non-restoring design, as were the subsequent Nos 2 and 3 types. Once the tablet had been removed, it had to travel through the single line section and be replaced in its companion instrument to release the section again. This meant that should a train failure occur in the single line section or a shunt beyond station limits, the tablet ''had'' to travel to the receiving instrument by foot or horse. However, there was a way in which a shunt could be performed without removing the tablet. This was achieved by a very similar means of the [[staff and ticket]] working system.\n\nThe later No 6 model however was a restoring design, which enabled the tablet to be placed back into the issuing instrument for shunting out of station limits. This increased flexibility and did not compromise safety. It also dispensed with the written authority in the staff and ticket system. Many No 1 instruments were modified with No 6 components to make them capable of restoring also.\n\n==Areas of use==\nThe [[Great Western Railway]] used the Tyer's No. 7 electric train tablet instrument at several locations, including the [[Brize Norton and Bampton railway station|Bampton]] to {{Stnlnk|Witney}} section.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=102}}\n\n[[Sri Lanka Railways]] is currently using this system at several locations, including the Kelani Valley line between Maradana and Avissawella in the Colombo District.\n\nThe Tyer's No. 6 tablet instrument was far more widespread in the UK and was adopted by most railway companies on single line installations. However, when the Tyer's No. 9 key token instrument was patented 40 years later in 1912, it began to replace the No. 6 due to it being compact, easier to use and had far fewer moving parts to service and repair.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nOn Britain's national network the use of Tyer's system is now almost extinct, with most lengthy single track lines having been converted to more modern systems such as [[Signalling block system|Tokenless Block]] or [[Radio Electronic Token Block]].  However, as of 2015  the Tyer Electric Token Block (using No 7 instruments and coloured perspex tablets)  remains in use on the [[Glasgow South Western Line|Stranraer Line]], between {{Stnlnk|Girvan}} and [[Dunragit]].\n\n===New Zealand's last tablet===\n[[File:Last tablet train advice 1994.jpg|right|thumb|Train Advice 5685, final tablet]]\n\nThe last tablet used on the New Zealand Rail Network was to allow train 1602 (Wellington - Masterton morning [[Wairarapa Connection]]) to travel between [[Featherston, New Zealand|Featherston]] and [[Masterton]] on the [[Wairarapa Line]] on Monday 4 July 1994. Even though the Masterton to Woodville tablet sections survived a few days longer, trains ran on a ''safe all'' where Train Control could allow a train to run without a tablet. \n\nThe last sections to use the tablet system were:\n* [[Featherston railway station]] - [[Carterton railway station]] - [[Masterton railway station]]\n* [[Masterton railway station]] - Pahiatua\n* Pahiatua - [[Woodville railway station, Manawatu-Wanganui|Woodville railway station]]\n\n==Heritage railways and museums==\nToday the tablet system lives on in many heritage railways and museums either as static / operational / interactive displays or as part of the heritage railway signalling system\n\n===Heritage railways===\n* [[Swanage Railway]],Dorset\n* [[Ferrymead Railway]], Christchurch\n* [[Silver Stream Railway]], Wellington\n* [[Glenbrook Vintage Railway]], Auckland\n* [[Kent & East Sussex Railway]], Tenterden Town\n\n===Railway museums===\n* Carterton Community & Railway Museum, [[Carterton railway station]]\n* [[Glenfinnan_railway_station|Glenfinnan Station Museum]]\n* [[Fell Engine Museum]], Featherston\n* [[National railway museum, Kadugannawa|Kadugannawa railway museum]], Sri Lanka\n\n===Other===\n* [[New Zealand Railway and Locomotive Society]] Ava Archive\n* [[Pahiatua Railcar Society]], Pahiatua Railway Station, New Zealand\n* Helensville Railway Station Trust, New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helensvillerail.org.nz/|title=Helensville Railway Station Precinct}}</ref>\n* [[Papatoetoe Railway Station Preservation Trust]], New Zealand\n* Taumarunui Rail Action Group, New Zealand\n* Ormondville Railway Station, New Zealand<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nzhistory.govt.nz/media/photo/ormondville-station|title=Ormondville Railway Station}}</ref>\n\n==Internal workings==\nBelow are a few photographs of the internal workings. This particular instrument has had the electric line clear addition and restoring functions added at a later date. It also carries the original plates by the plunger and commutator which were often removed.\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-4.JPG|Left side showing the tablet restoring lever, line clear release and the coils\nImage:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-9.JPG|The top portion where the commutator and indicator mechanism and circuits are housed\nimage:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-8.JPG|Top view showing the indicator coils and part of the commutator mechanism\nimage:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-13.JPG|Detailed photograph of the commutator mechanism and the push rods that interact with the indicators\nImage:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-3.JPG|The right side showing the tablet replacing mechanism and rods to the tablet status indicators\n</gallery>\n\n== Accidents ==\n=== Before tokens ===\n* [[Menheniot railway station]]\n\n=== After tokens ===\n* [[Abermule train collision|Abermule]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* ''New Zealand Railway and Tramway Atlas'', 4th ed Quail Map Company, 1993\n* W.N. Cameron ''A Line Of Railway'', NZR&LS Wellington 1976\n*{{cite book |last=Faith |first=Nicholas |title=Derail: Why Trains Crash |year=2000 |publisher=Channel 4/Macmillan |location=London |isbn=0-7522-7165-2 |ref=harv }}\n*{{cite book |last=Vaughan |first=Adrian |title=A Pictorial Record of Great Western Signalling |isbn=0-86093-346-6 |publisher=Oxford Publishing Co. |location=Poole |origyear=1973 |year=1984 |edition=2nd |ref=harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Token instruments}}\n* [http://www.valleysignals.org.nz Valley Signals]\n\n[[Category:Railway signalling in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Railway signaling in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Globalize|date=August 2008}}\n\n'''Tyer's Electric Train Tablet''' system is a form of [[railway signalling]] for [[Single track (rail)|single line]] railways used in several countries; it was first devised in Great Britain by engineer {{Interlanguage link multi|Edward Tyer|lb}} after the [[Thorpe rail accident]] of 1874, which left 21 people dead.{{sfn|Faith|2000|p=44}} It was used in New Zealand for close to 100 years until June 1994.\nThe system used a hard disk called a ''tablet'', a form of [[Token (railway signalling)|token]]. \n\nThe purpose of the system was to use the tablet as a physical guarantee to the traincrew that their train had exclusive right of way on the single line section. Without this they could not proceed beyond the section signal which protected entry to the single line. \n\nWith advances in electrical locking of the [[lever frame]] within the [[signal box]], the tablet instrument also electrically locked the section signal lever. This was marked with a white stripe on the red background.\n\n==Construction==\n[[File:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-1.JPG|thumb|Main view of No. 6 instrument showing the restoring lever and the tablet tray in the \"out\" position]]\n\nAn instrument was placed at each end of the single-track section that they were to control. They were connected together electrically in such a way that operation of one would depend on operations carried out using the other.\n\nThere were various incarnations of instruments developed by Tyer & Co. Below are the more commonly found ones:\n\nThe Tyer's no. 7 tablet instrument consists of a wooden case, on top of which is a metal slide, a switch plunger, a bell plunger and an electric current indicator. On the front is an indicator which may show either of three indications: \"Line Closed\"; \"Train Approaching\" and \"Train on Line\". Below this there is a second slide, which has three positions: fully home, withdrawn half way, and fully withdrawn. The three indications correspond to the three positions of the slide. The case contains several tablets; they are removed from the instrument using the bottom slide, and replaced using the top slide. The instrument was so constructed that if a tablet had been withdrawn from either instrument of a pair, no further tablets could be withdrawn until the withdrawn tablet had been placed either in the other instrument, or in the same instrument from which it had been withdrawn.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=121}}\n\nThe Tyer's no. 6 tablet instrument is cast iron framed that has a movable drawer at the front which issues and receives the tablets. On the left hand side is a lever to reseat the tablet when it is replaced into the magazine. It has wooden side cheeks to access the complicated mechanism and a tombstone shaped wooden case on the top which houses the bell plunger, commutator and the tablet indicators for up and down trains. At the very top was the [[galvanometer]]. The [[British absolute block signalling|signalling bell]] associated with the machine is separate so could be located on the block shelf or wall mounted above the instrument.\n\n===Tablets===\nTablets are in the form of a disc made of metal or fibre (with a gunmetal weight at the top of the magazine), engraved with the names of the stations between which it is valid, and also provided with notches (also called configurations) or other indentations to ensure that it would fit only one pair of instruments. They were often painted in distinctive colours as an additional visual identification in areas where consecutive sections could each be controlled using the same type of instrument. The diameter of the tablets varied between the different patterns of instrument: those for the No 1 were the largest, the smallest were for the No 5 and No 7, whilst the Nos 2,3,4 and 6 all used tablets about {{convert|4.5|in|mm}} in diameter.\n\n==Operation==\n[[File:Tyer's No. 6 Tablet Instrument-11.JPG|thumb|The indicators showing a tablet has been issued for an Up train from this instrument]]\nThe system required each station at the end of each section to be staffed, the staff member would communicate with the staff member at the other end of the section with a bell code to release a tablet.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=121}}\n\nTo release a tablet at station A to send a train to station B:\n* Both machines must be in a closed state\n* Operator at station A sends a bell code to station B asking if line is clear for the train\n* If clear, operator at station B will repeat the bell code to acknowledge\n* Station A operator holds down the bell plunger\n* Station B operator presses his/her switch plunger with one hand, and with the other pulls out the bottom slide half-way; the instrument now shows a \"Train Approaching\" indication\n* Station B operator holds down the bell plunger\n* Station A operator presses his/her switch plunger with one hand, and with the other pulls the bottom slide to its full extent; the instrument now shows a \"Train on Line\" indication and releases a tablet from the lower slide\n* Station A operator hands the tablet to the driver of the train heading to station B\n\nTo close up each machine once the train has arrived at station B from station A:\n* The train driver hands the tablet to station B operator\n* Station B operator draws out the top slide, places the tablet in it, and closes the top and then the bottom slide; the instrument now shows a \"Line Closed\" indication\n* Station B operator sends a bell code to station A (denoting \"Train out of Section\"), holding the plunger down on the last stroke\n* Station A operator holds down his switch plunger, and closes the bottom slide; the instrument now shows a \"Line Closed\" indication\n* Both machines are now in closed states ready for the process to start again for another train\n\nThe original Tyer's No. 1 instrument was a non-restoring design, as were the subsequent Nos 2 and 3 types. Once the tablet had been removed, it had to travel through the single line section and be replaced in its companion instrument to release the section again. This meant that should a train failure occur in the single line section or a shunt beyond station limits, the tablet ''had'' to travel to the receiving instrument by foot or horse. However, there was a way in which a shunt could be performed without removing the tablet. This was achieved by a very similar means of the [[staff and ticket]] working system.\n\nThe later No 6 model however was a restoring design, which enabled the tablet to be placed back into the issuing instrument for shunting out of station limits. This increased flexibility and did not compromise safety. It also dispensed with the written authority in the staff and ticket system. Many No 1 instruments were modified with No 6 components to make them capable of restoring also.\n\n==Areas of use==\nThe [[Great Western Railway]] used the Tyer's No. 7 electric train tablet instrument at several locations, including the [[Brize Norton and Bampton railway station|Bampton]] to {{Stnlnk|Witney}} section.{{sfn|Vaughan|1984|p=102}}\n\n[[Sri Lanka Railways]] is currently using this system at several locations, including the Kelani Valley line between Maradana and Avissawella in the Colombo District.\n\nThe Tyer's No. 6 tablet instrument was far more widespread in the UK and was adopted by most railway companies on single line installations. However, when the Tyer's No. 9 key token instrument was patented 40 years later in 1912, it began to replace the No. 6 due to it being compact, easier to use and had far fewer moving parts to service and repair.{{Citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\nOn Britain's national network the use of Tyer's system is now almost extinct, with most lengthy single track lines having been converted to more modern systems such as [[Signalling block system|Tokenless Block]] or [[Radio Electronic Token Block]].  However, as of 2015  the Tyer Electric Token Block (using No 7 instruments and coloured perspex tablets)  remains in use on the [[Glasgow South Western Line|Stranraer Line]], between {{Stnlnk|Girvan}} and [[Dunragit]].\n\n===New Zealand's last tablet===\n[[File:Last tablet train advice 1994.jpg|right|thumb|Train Advice 5685, final tablet]]\n\nThe last tablet used on the New Zealand Rail Network was to allow train 1602 (Wellington - Masterton morning [[Wairarapa Connection]]) to travel between [[Featherston, New Zealand|Featherston]] and [[Masterton]] on the [[Wairarapa Line]] on Monday 4 July 1994. Even though the Masterton to Woodville tablet sections survived a few days longer, trains ran on a ''safe all'' where Train Control could allow a train to run without a tablet. \n\nThe last sections to use the tablet system were:\n* [[Featherston railway station]] - [[Carterton railway station]] - [[Masterton railway station]]\n* [[Masterton railway station]] - Pahiatua\n* Pahiatua - [[Woodville railway station]]\n\n==Heritage railways and museums==\nToday the tablet system lives on in many heritage railways and museums either as static / operational / interactive displays or as part of the heritage railway signalling system\n\n===Heritage railways===\n* [[Swanage Railway]],Dorset\n* [[Ferrymead Railway]], Christchurch\n* [[Silver Stream Railway]], Wellington\n* [[Glenbrook Vintage Railway]], Auckland\n* [[Kent & East Sussex Railway]], Tenterden Town\n\n===Railway museums===\n* Carterton Community & Railway Museum, [[Carterton railway station]]\n* [[Glenfinnan_railway_station|Glenfinnan Station Museum]]\n* [[Fell Engine Museum]], Featherston\n* [[National railway museum, Kadugannawa|Kadugannawa railway museum]], Sri Lanka\n\n===Other===\n* [[